7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, are shown in a theatre this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans could find more revealing, in an interview with Jobs recently rediscovered, which has been depopulated as a advancement of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the commercial processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a young man of flow diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds (Triumph of the Nerds) about the dawns of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, Jobs had barely been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working hard in his new NeXT computer company, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said that the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs died that a complete copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This file material, slightly reedited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview, which arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate deep interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and commercial strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points during the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly suspending his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism goes to the surface, where it seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster on issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the age of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of computer science.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there is something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how they can and should be things.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked: "Why do you do things?" and the answers that give you invariably are: "Oh, that's just the way you do."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes their efforts to simplify Apple's accounting in detail.
Unconvinced by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made with a good copper eye, and then adjusted with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that assured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the Pope's joke:
Jobs tells the "Blue Box" that he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to hack effectively the phone company and make free long distance calls.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here when describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
Describes how he and Wozniak tried the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were involving things around the world about a dozen times and shouting through the public phone and returning a minute later to the public phone at the door next door," Jobs says with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think there never existed Apple without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak with the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into carcasses just before the Pope himself was awakened to go to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 years old, hunting spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the telephone guide and made a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company that had seen at that age and formed my vision of what was a company and what good they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first ever-made table computer."
He was as big as a suitcase, he had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with him.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
About improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the march.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of base plates, he asked a client if he could mount the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while in Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
