Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's rebirth, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"He says you work in IBM or Xerox, so you're doing better photocopiers and printers, and what?"
You have the monopoly of the market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so these kinds of people who end up leading companies and product managers are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position is rotting because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the big idea evolves, changes and grows."
Much is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to do - some things you can't make the electrons, the glass makes them, the robots make them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - fit them all at once...
At the end it all comes down to the taste - it goes down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to the things you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed of stealing big ideas.
What made Macintosh big was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were by chance the best computer scientists in the world.
