Liar has destroyed race and convulsed countries.
The congressman for New York and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the ridiculous with his dissidents quickly rebutted by irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with infringements in the financing of the campaign related to the coverage of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who would live it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps are widely spread in school and university exams.
There have been cases where teachers have given the answers of the exams to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How deceptive are we?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades in prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about lies have been rebutted.
The liars do look into the eyes.
Not always tart mudean, bluffing, rubbed or restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are hard to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can reach the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies", while women say more lies "oriented towards others" -- usually to protect the feelings of someone -- that married people less frequently lie to their couples than those who are not married (but the lies they usually say to be "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty when you lie to him.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called creating a basic line.
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Watch the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better to know if someone usually beats his foot all the time to avoid making unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of misleading, verbal and nonverbal behavior.
Consider these groups of behaviour as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their history, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards a way out, change their posture significantly or exhibit a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated breath of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions have ended.
Often interrogators falsely show that the interview has ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson laid his paw to the bottom and used the past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the possibilities of anyone to avoid being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
