MSS Announces Protocol to Find Gene of Obesity
Leads Social Insurance an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Specialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate either in the right or not, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Poniente State of Mexico) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (Eastern Mexico State).
Once the objective of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics regarding the development of obesity and to identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the celebration of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, it stated that the objective is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
You will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger such diseases as diabetes or renal failure.
He noted that on Saturdays all participants are applied anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels (the aim is to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is driven by the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 percent in obesity, and in the case of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed,' noted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by their genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess of energy that we consume (calories) and is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows them to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (cantonosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the probability of metabolic and even predisabetes disorders.
The information is handled in a confidential way, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are told each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic sufferings: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the television and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugared beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, et cetera) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would prevent berries
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mix with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 basins each rain season in the Mexican Valley Metropolitan Zone, warned Rafael Herrera Najera, researcher of the UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or, even, completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the berries, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and hence the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the most heavy part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor their characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but that it is changing during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the surface layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were to be modified asphalt it would be even better spread, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abundant, is placed a last layer called tread folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, an sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
