On November 4th, a logger from Cali's ITC went to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", through his fingerprints.
Of the seven trophoscopes working in the ITC section, that week he played the "availability" shift to Eliasar González, a man from Port Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of the Chocó, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valle and, after carrying out the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of the hands and feet.
The operating week against Alfonso Cano alias to Elias warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
Friday night he left for the Caucasus on a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so they asked him to carry the decactillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplant and a flashlight, Elias compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye failed him: he was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was the chief chief of the Farcs.
Searching for the print
For a dictator of the Sijín of Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliasar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactioscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can become a key to the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many delinquents present false ballots or have no papers.
We take fingerprints and search them in the database.
The investigator reported that, in a case of theft, he was touched to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to take out a fingerprint, but in that case we could get the mark of the whole hand and identify the criminal, who had participated in different thefts," she recalled.
The fingerprints may also discard or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a family member could be a suspect of the crime and, in fact, a trace in the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
An ITC ticist explained that in the objects "the traces are taken out with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Register.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
