In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements for this.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which included the participation of six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in such a way that assisted suicide and euthanasia are permitted, when the patient is given such an option and has been tried competent to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada occupies the tenth position, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, as indicated by the experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Quebec, where 86% of the deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that they do not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, that they have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or are not criminal offences, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not caused an abuse of their application, that is, the use of euthanasia or suicide assisted with persons not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excess were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians, favouring euthanasia
Let us remember that 85 per cent of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia, as they are of the opinion that it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, as indicated by an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66 per cent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of older or disabled persons are less valuable.
With regard to persons who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents felt that a trial should not be initiated against them.
With regard to the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, as the authors of the report indicate.
Furthermore, among its recommendations, it suggests that the Criminal Code states that withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient rejects assistance at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, not only in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, be considered euthanasia and subject to the same procedures.
Other experts demonstrate reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations regarding the conclusions of the report of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a health specialist, has described the “extreme” position of the experts who sign the report, among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to those who are terminally ill.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 can ask for help to commit suicide," says Deschamps, who yesterday consulted a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report appear to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations."
Health Law Specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" with regard to the conclusions of the report, which called "a demonstration for euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, particularly calls into question the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
