Energy policy:
the facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be dealt with considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an election meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, there will be an increasing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
This is not the case with Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor with Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite some examples, continue to be determined with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resumed the construction of a power station interrupted after the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality runs counter to such discourse.
The choice of Berlin is going to mean an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, harmful effects will be noted.
The case of Denmark should be taken into account.
European champion in the wind sector, of which 30% of its electricity is obtained, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to wind interference; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would entail a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would remain realistic to the wonderful statements on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not show opposition by principle to this type of energy, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 head jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets that can create non-movable jobs.
If France decided to give up nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of most of these SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros per year in French nuclear equipment and services exports.
What electrician would charge an EPR designed to function sixty years, when your manufacturer's collapse is expected?
In order to solve the nuclear energy equation, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Security Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamenville.
Our well-known professional teams are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences either for people or for the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failings.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural catastrophes, which resulted in the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as the previous two did.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
As they study all the electrical actors who want to build a power station, the interruption of their construction in Flamenville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to assume leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from a variety of points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "the country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who have jumped the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the journal Libération of 23 May) proclaiming from the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waitresses".
However, it is rarely economically analysed.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "90,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million migrant workers," while on the left, the tone set Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will help solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular the underskilled, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and primarily work in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country that lacks anesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the wages and employment of the nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows represents a rise in the long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized Nobel Prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they provide an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches 30 years of age will make a net contribution (increasing less expenses) of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points that were missing "with his teeth."
These teeth, which discouraged the immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
