Cards with "no contact" chip are generalized
The world hall of chip cards starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an increase of 11% in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to estimates from the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is that of non-contact technology, which allows you to pay for common transport or purchases simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year 460 million cards will be sold worldwide with no contact chip, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its contribution should continue to increase in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the world market for chip cards (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa cards are being used without contact.
But the big surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million Pass MasterCard cards this year without contact.
To get the top gear, however, banks need to make them available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have committed themselves to spreading systematically in the future, among their customers, bank cards with no contact in the system," says Gérard Nebouy, director general of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for carrying out transactions.
"They're turning back."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units in 2012 worldwide," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Agricultural Credit Bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and June in Caen.
The iPhones will be equipped with about 200 customers and collaborators with a fund that allows the payment without contact.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the General Society has also stated yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact via their mobile phone.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, on which it had long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Algiers "has the certainty."
"The way in which both organizations operate and the reports of intelligence services demonstrate that they are cooperating," he explained, without further details.
Paris seems to reach a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the gateways.
Kidnapped in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the debris of the intervention, French and Nigerian researchers discovered several telephone chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of calls indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two figures particularly captured the interest of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who has long stayed in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the town of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who, supposedly, is close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly expect to have more formal evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in Boko Haram's evolution and discourses or in his operating modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices and of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as a community of enlightened little interest.
A quick hit
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist magnet Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic Emirates in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is living a fast success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect from the sharia, while its militants are engaged in the fight against the wicked central government.
The latter focus primarily on churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and the attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and recorded 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern feuds.
Christmas has claimed an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular against the police-protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of these.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters became its first international goal.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would cover from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is disturbing all security experts.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Shebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information."
